LAGOS – A coalition of women groups have sustained a pro-Affirmative Action protest at the National Assembly in Abuja after federal lawmakers three out all the inclusion bills listed for consideration during the recently concluded Constitution Review exercise by the legislature. In a press statement on Friday, signed by Dr. Abiola Akiyode-Afolabi, Saudatu Mahdi, Ebere Ifedu, Co-Convener, Womanifesto, and WRAPA Secretary General, Chairperson Women in Politics, demanded amongst other things the urgent re-convening, reconsideration, and passage of the all women and gender-related bills by the National Assembly. Part of the statement read: “The passage of the Gender and Equal Opportunities (GEOB) Bill, currently before the Senate, resuscitation and passage of the Bill on ‘Support for Women Participation in Elective and Appointive positions, immediate domestication of the African Charters Protocol on the Rights of Women in Africa, which Nigeria ratified in 2004. We’ve Taken Out Most Self-Acclaimed Terror Leaders –Air Marshal… APC Crisis: Buhari Breaks Silence, Sues For Peace “And the immediate domestication of the UN Convention on Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women (CEDAW), ratified by Nigeria since 1985.” According to the women, “The world stood still on March 1, 2022, when the Nigerian male-dominated National Assembly members declined their vested responsibility to recalibrate the brazen imbalance in the governance of our country. “This reinforced the major barriers in the path to addressing age-long discrimination against women’s representation and participation in governance. “It also affirmed the reasons for the stunted development of our country, while assenting to a continuation of the cycle of discrimination, abuse, and cultural bias against your very own, your female relatives gathered here.”